text=(:if [ authgroup @tas || authgroup @admins || equal {$Author} '' ]:)%0a%0a(:toggle id=gi show="show grading interface" hide="hide grading interface":)%0a%0a>>id=gi%3c%3c%0a%0a[[GradebookArticles.{$Name}|See article in gradebook]] \\%0a[[{$FullName}?action=diff|See all changes to article]] \\%0a[[{$FullName}?action=edit|Edit this page]] \\%0aStatus: {GradebookArticles.{$Name}$:Status} %0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradeitem:)%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradingcomment:)%0a%0a>>%3c%3c%0a%0a----%0a%0a(:ifend:)%0a%0a[[!{$:Category}]]%0a%0a!The Spanish epenthesis (/e/ insertion preceding s+consonant clusters) %0a%0a:Author: dani26%0a%0a'''Summary:''' \\%0a%0a[[#summary]]%0a%0aHow /e/ is prepended under certain conditions to conform to internal phonotactic constraints%0a%0a[[#summaryends]]%0a%0a----%0a[[#content]]%0a%0aIn Spanish (Indo-European), a well-known phonotactic constraint is that word-initial s+consonant clusters are not allowed (1). As a native speaker of both Spanish and English, I always found it curious how my relatives (who learned English after their native Spanish) would insert /e/ prior to certain words in English:%0a  /estop/ instead of /stop/%0a  /espeak/ instead of /speak/%0a%0aAs it would turn out, this is a systematic rule that occurs internally within the language, as well as when accepting loanwords from other languages. The rule as usually stated is written: (2)%0a%0a  Ø --> e / #_sC%0a%0aMy relatives were projecting their native tongue's phonotactic constraints onto English! %0a%0aInternal examples:%0a%0a  "escribir"%0a  "escolar"%0a  "eslavo"%0a  "España"%0a  "esperar"%0a%0aNote that this rule is not applicable to sC clusters in other locations, because the constraint is only for word-initial clusters:%0a%0a  "inscribir" (whereas "escribir" does exhibit the constraint)%0a  "prosperar" (contrast with "esperar")%0a%0aWhen Spanish adds words from other languages without this constraint, it's imposed:%0a%0a  "estable" (stable)%0a  "estado" (statum)%0a%0a----Sources-----%0a1: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC4870387/%0a2: https://summit.sfu.ca/_flysystem/fedora/sfu_migrate/3149/b12131015.pdf%0a%0a[[#contentends]]%0a----%0a----%0a%0a!!Expansions:%0a[[#expansions]]%0a%0a[[#expansionsend]]%0a%0a----%0a%25red%25 '''Add an expansion:'''%0a%0a(:if [ exists GradebookExpansions.{$Name}-{$Author} || equal {$Author} {$:Author} ] :)%0a%0a(:elseif [ equal {Profiles.{$Author}$:andrewid} '' || equal {Profiles.{$Author}$:section} '' ] :)%0a%0aYou must enter your andrew ID and section before submitting an expansion. %0a%0a(:else:)%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#newexpansion:)%0a%0a(:ifend:)%0a%0a----%0a----%0a%0a!!Comments%0a%0a%0a%0a%0a----%0a(:if equal {$Author} {$:Author}:)%0a!!Change article category%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#changearticlecategory:)%0a(:ifend:)%0a%0a%0a(:Section: F:)%0a(:Category: PhonologicalPhenomenaInSpokenLanguages:)%0a(:Title: The Spanish epenthesis (/e/ insertion preceding s+consonant clusters) :)
